{"id":"2107.13495","submitter":"Mihai-Alin Badiu","authors":"Mihai-Alin Badiu and Justin P. Coon","title":"Structural Complexity of One-Dimensional Random Geometric Graphs","comments":"44 pages, 9 figures; revised some of results; significant additional\n  results included","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.IT math.IT","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  We study the richness of the ensemble of graphical structures (i.e.,\nunlabeled graphs) of the one-dimensional random geometric graph model defined\nby $n$ nodes randomly scattered in $[0,1]$ that connect if they are within the\nconnection range $r\\in[0,1]$. We provide bounds on the number of possible\nstructures which give universal upper bounds on the structural entropy that\nhold for any $n$, $r$ and distribution of the node locations. For fixed $r$,\nthe number of structures is $\\Theta(a^{2n})$ with $a=a(r)=2\n\\cos{\\left(\\frac{\\pi}{\\lceil 1/r \\rceil+2}\\right)}$, and therefore the\nstructural entropy is upper bounded by $2n\\log_2 a(r) + O(1)$. For large $n$,\nwe derive bounds on the structural entropy normalized by $n$, and evaluate them\nfor independent and uniformly distributed node locations. When the connection\nrange $r_n$ is $O(1/n)$, the obtained upper bound is given in terms of a\nfunction that increases with $n r_n$ and asymptotically attains $2$ bits per\nnode. If the connection range is bounded away from zero and one, the upper and\nlower bounds decrease linearly with $r$, as $2(1-r)$ and $(1-r)\\log_2 e$,\nrespectively. When $r_n$ is vanishing but dominates $1/n$ (e.g., $r_n \\propto\n\\ln n / n$), the normalized entropy is between $\\log_2 e \\approx 1.44$ and $2$\nbits per node. We also give a simple encoding scheme for random structures that\nrequires $2$ bits per node. The upper bounds in this paper easily extend to the\nentropy of the labeled random graph model, since this is given by the\nstructural entropy plus a term tha