{"id":"2107.13552","submitter":"Eric R. Sharpe","authors":"D. Robbins, E. Sharpe, T. Vandermeulen","title":"Anomaly resolution via decomposition","comments":"LaTeX, 22 pages; v2: typos fixed","journal-ref":"Int. J. Mod. Phys. A 36 (2021) 2150220","doi":"10.1142/S0217751X21502201","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper we apply decomposition to orbifolds with quantum symmetries to\nresolve anomalies. Briefly, it has been argued by e.g. Wang-Wen-Witten,\nTachikawa that an anomalous orbifold can sometimes be resolved by enlarging the\norbifold group so that the pullback of the anomaly to the larger group is\ntrivial. For this procedure to resolve the anomaly, one must specify a set of\nphases in the larger orbifold, whose form is implicit in the extension\nconstruction. There are multiple choices of consistent phases, which give rise\nto physically distinct resolutions. We apply decomposition, and find that\ntheories with enlarged orbifold groups are equivalent to (disjoint unions of\ncopies of) orbifolds by nonanomalous subgroups of the original orbifold group.\nIn effect, decomposition implies that enlarging the orbifold group is\nequivalent to making it smaller. We provide a general conjecture for such\ndescriptions, which we check in a number of examples.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 28 Jul 2021 18:00:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 26 Nov 2021 20:02:30 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-30"}
